    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-04T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-04T19:00:00-05:00" n="81"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.24/1–3046: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-04T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 4, 1946—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>177. ReEmbs 213 Jan 30.<note n="2" xml:id="d81fn1">Not printed.</note> Dept has
                    no objection to <gloss target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> sending 10,000 tires to
                        <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss>, providing none are taken from <gloss
                        target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> production up to and through Jan 31 in
                    accordance with oral pledges made at time of cancellation of tire and tube
                        agreement.<note n="3" xml:id="d81fn2">For a summary of the agreement, see
                            <ref target="frus1942v05#pg_719">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 719</ref>, footnote 87; with regard to
                        its termination, see <ref target="frus1945v09#pg_712">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1945, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ix</hi>,
                            telegram 3437, November 16, 1945, from Rio de Janeiro, p.
                        712</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Believe both impossible and unwise suspend embarking tires for <gloss
                        target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss>. First shipment totalling 4,000 tires left US
                    for <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> on Feb 2 and balance to be shipped over
                    period of 90 days.</p>
                <p>As stated in Depts 126 of Jan 25,<note n="2" xml:id="d81fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    is understood <gloss target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> would be included in any
                    international allocation plan drawn up with <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss>
                    cooperation and that to extent <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> not indicated
                    as source for all of wheat considered by <gloss target="#t_CFB1">CFB</gloss> to
                    be share of <gloss target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> in light of world deficit,
                    other sources would be indicated. Since effecting of a coordinated pattern for
                    shipments from export countries may take considerable time, is proper <gloss
                        target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> make arrangements with <gloss target="#t_Braz1"
                        >Braz</gloss> to assure continuation of shipments from that country, which
                    is logical source. <gloss target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> needs could not, as
                    implied in <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>s 213, have already been
                    “definitely provided for by Combined Board” apart from cooperation of <gloss
                        target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> in making available her wheat for export. This
                    true because of great world shortage (see Depcirairgram Dec. 26<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d81fn4">Not printed.</note>). Furthermore any <gloss
                        target="#t_CFB1">CFB</gloss> allocation which might be recommended would not
                    exclude necessity for bilateral arrangements between the exporting and importing
                    countries implementing allocations indicated. The sooner therefore <gloss
                        target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> reaches an understanding with <gloss
                        target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> in this matter the sooner will she have
                    received the assurances with regard to fulfillment of her import needs which she
                    so much desires.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_CFB1">CFB</gloss> will only make “definite allocations of
                    Argentine wheat” (reEmbs 231 Feb. 1, 1946<note n="2" xml:id="d81fn5">Not
                        printed.</note>) if and when international allocation set up. Prerequisite
                    for any such allocation or joint programming is cooperation of <gloss
                        target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> in working out amounts and destinations of <pb
                        facs="0131" n="113" xml:id="pg_113"/> wheat to be exported from that country
                    within a given period. Any wheat quota arranged for by <gloss target="#t_Braz1"
                        >Braz</gloss> with <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss> in exchange for tires
                    would be deductible from the total for <gloss target="#t_Braz1"
                    >Braz</gloss>.</p>
                <p>It is not contemplated that <gloss target="#t_Braz1">Braz</gloss> stated
                    requirement can be fully met, particularly for first half 1946. A total of
                    460,000 tons for first half has been tentatively proposed, most of it to come
                    from <gloss target="#t_Arg1">Arg</gloss>. This figure is not at all definitive
                    and is subject to further reduction if the prospective world wheat supply
                    position worsens. This amount could however be taken now as indicating an
                    absolute maximum for the half year.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
